{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:31:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:31:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12446"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.5,0.12,0.17,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49643"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4954"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34930"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2918"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13688"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49643"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents with a two-month history of headache, facial swelling, and ankle swelling. On further questioning, he has noticed frothy, but normal coloured, urine. He was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes mellitus 10 years ago, for which he takes metformin. He ceased intravenous drug use six months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, pulse is 82/min, respiratory rate 16/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 99% on room air. There is bilateral pitting oedema of his ankles. Chest examination reveals clear breath sounds bilaterally with no signs of respiratory distress. The abdominal examination indicates a soft, non-tender abdomen without hepatomegaly or splenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA urine dipstick demonstrates 3+ proteinuria and his blood tests show an albumin level of 22g/L (32-45g/L). A renal biopsy is performed which shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Elight microscopy: segmental obliteration of the glomerular tuft\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eelectron microscopy: effacement of foot processes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Minimal change disease","Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis","Membranous nephropathy","Diabetic nephropathy","IgA nephropathy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the provided clinical presentation and results of his investigations, the correct diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Efocal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS).\u003C/strong\u003E The characteristic features such as intravenous drug use history, peripheral oedema, frothy urine, pitting oedema, hypertension, proteinuria, hypoalbuminaemia, with the specific renal pathology observed on electron microscopy (foot process effacement and segmental obliteration of the glomerular tuft) are consistent with FSGS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFocal segmental glomerulosclerosis is characterised by localised scarring in glomeruli and commonly associated with nephrotic syndrome and hypertension. It can affect individuals of various ages, including adults. In the context of the provided case, the gradual onset of symptoms, electron microscopy findings of foot process effacement, and segmental obliteration align well with FSGS, making this the likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntravenous (IV) drug use is linked to FSGS due to the direct nephrotoxic effects of substances injected, such as heroin. The injected substances may induce immune complex formation, depositing in the glomeruli and causing inflammation. Additionally, renal ischaemia resulting from IV drug use contributes to glomerular injury and scarring. FSGS is a common cause of nephrotic syndrome, characterised by proteinuria and hypoalbuminaemia, with specific histological changes like foot process effacement observed on electron microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinimal change disease\u003C/strong\u003E (MCD) is a primary glomerular disorder typically observed in children, with its hallmark manifestation being generalised oedema, proteinuria, and hypoalbuminaemia. This condition often has an abrupt onset and is marked by the absence of significant changes in renal histology visible under light microscopy. Unlike the presented case, MCD rarely involves hypertension and is more commonly diagnosed in paediatric populations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMembranous nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E involves immune complex deposition in the glomerular basement membrane, typically presenting with nephrotic syndrome. However, hypertension and foot process effacement, as seen in the electron microscopy findings of the patient, are not typical features of this condition. Membranous nephropathy is more commonly diagnosed in adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETypically, \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetic nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E develops over an extended period in individuals with longstanding diabetes, with microalbuminuria and macroalbuminuria progressing to nephrotic syndrome. . Renal biopsies in diabetic nephropathy typically reveal diffuse glomerulosclerosis under light microscopy, with thickening of the glomerular basement membrane and expansion of the mesangium. On electron microscopy, characteristic findings include the presence of nodular glomerulosclerosis, thickening of the glomerular basement membrane, and mesangial expansion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by the deposition of IgA immune complexes in the glomerular mesangium, is considered less likely in this case due to the absence of haematuria. Typically, IgA nephropathy presents with recurrent episodes of gross or microscopic haematuria. However, in this case, there is no mention of any signs of haematuria. Moreover, the renal biopsy findings in the case reveal segmental obliteration of the glomerular tuft and foot process effacement, which are not typical features associated with IgA nephropathy, known for mesangial proliferation. The absence of key diagnostic features makes IgA nephropathy a less probable explanation for the patient\u0027s condition. In IgA nephropathy, light microscopy often shows mesangial proliferation and the presence of IgA deposits, while electron microscopy reveals mesangial immune complex deposits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS) typically presents with nephrotic syndrome (oedema, nephrotic range proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, hypercholesterolemia)."],"references":["Guruswamy Sangameswaran KD, Hashmi MF, Baradhi KM. Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis. [Updated 2023 Feb 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532272/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34930"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12446"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"it